heir novels, stories and autobiographies. Drawing on advice literature, medical texts and feminist polemic, it demonstrates how these narratives responded to contemporary political controversies around the vote, women’s work, sexual inversion and birth control, as well as examining the impact of the First World War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish fictionxWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fiction. 0aLesbians in literature. 0aSingle women in literature. 0aWidows in literature. 0aWomen in literature. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aHeteronormativity.  aLesbians.  aSingleness.  aSpinsters.  aWidows.1 aLiggins, Emma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packagez978311128357940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526111654423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526111654/original  a978-3-11-128357-9  Manchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packageb2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles